      "side": 1,
      "message": "IMO, this is taking things a bit too far because this is adding testing things into the real, concrete type. Go has interfaces and I think that\u0027s what should be used here. You can drop the timeFunc type declaration and the struct field function calls throughout Log and Stage and then do this like:\n\n  type LogI interface {  // \u003c---Use LogI in all function signatures\n      Stages() []*Stage\n      Time()   time.Time\n  }\n\n  type Log struct {\n      stages  []*Stage\n  }\n\n  func (l *Log) stages() []*Stage {\n      return stages\n  }\n\n  func (l *Log) time() time.Time {\n      return time.Now()\n  }\n\n\n// In tests\n\n  type FakeLog struct {\n      stages  []*Stage\n      time    time.Time\n  }\n\n  func (l *FakeLog) stages() []*Stage {\n      return stages\n  }\n\n  func (l *FakeLog) time() time.Time {\n      return time\n  }\n\n...\n\nDon\u0027t feel strongly, though.",
      "range": {
